(68, 0, 13, '1', '9', 2019, '4', 'EE2004', 'Digital Signal Processing', '11', 'Course Details\r\nTo teach the fundamentals of Digital Signal Processing\r\n\r\nCourse Content:Review of Signals and Systems: Discrete time complex exponentials and other basic signalsâ€”scaling of the independent axis and differences from its continuous-time counterpartâ€”system properties (linearity, time-invariance, memory, causality, BIBO stability)â€”LTI systems described by linear constant coefficient difference equations (LCCDE)â€”impulse response and convolution. Discrete-Time Fourier Transform (DTFT): Complex exponentials as eigensignals of LTI systemsâ€”DTFT definitionâ€”inversion formulaâ€”propertiesâ€”relationship to continuous-time Fourier series (CTFS). Z-Transform: Generalized complex exponentials as eigensignals of LTI systemsâ€”z-transform definitionâ€”region of convergence (RoC)â€”properties of RoCâ€”properties of the z-transformâ€”inverse z-transform methods (partial fraction expansion, power series method, contour integral approach)â€”pole-zero plotsâ€”time-domain responses of simple pole-zero plotsâ€”RoC implications of causality and stability. Frequency Domain Analysis of LTI Systems: Frequency response of systems with rational transfer functionâ€”definitions of magnitude and phase responseâ€”geometric method of frequency response evaluation from pole-zero plotâ€”frequency response of single complex zero/poleâ€”frequency response of simple configurations (second order resonator, notch filter, averaging filter, comb filter, allpass systems)â€”phase responseâ€”definition of principal phaseâ€”zero-phase responseâ€”group delayâ€”phase response of single complex zero/poleâ€”extension to higher order systemsâ€”effect of a unit circle zero on the phase responseâ€”zero-phase response representation of systems with rational transfer functionâ€”minimum phase and allpass systemsâ€”constant group delay and its consequencesâ€”generalized linear phaseâ€”conditions that have to be met for a filter to have generalized linear phaseâ€”four types of linear phase FIR filtersâ€”on the zero locations of a linear phase FIR filterâ€”constrained zeros at z = 1 and at z = -1 and their implications on choice of filters Type I through Type IV when designing filtersâ€”frequency response expressions for Type I through Type IV filters. Sampling: Impulse train samplingâ€”relationship between impulse trained sampled continuous-time signal spectrum and the DTFT of its discrete-time counterpartâ€”scaling of the frequency axisâ€”relationship between true frequency and digital frequencyâ€”reconstruction through sinc interpolationâ€”aliasingâ€”effect of sampling at a discontinuous pointâ€”relationship between analog and digital sincâ€”effects of oversamplingâ€”discrete-time processing of continuous-time signals. Discrete Fourier Transform (DFT): Definition of the DFT and inverse DFTâ€”relationship to discrete-time Fourier seriesâ€”matrix representationâ€”DFT as the samples of the DTFT and the implied periodicity of the time-domain signalâ€”recovering the DTFT from the DFTâ€”circular shift of signal and the \"index mod N\" conceptâ€”properties of the DFTâ€”circular convolution and its relationship with linear convolutionâ€”effect of zero paddingâ€”introduction to the Fast Fourier Transform (FFT) algorithmâ€”decimation-in-time and decimation-in-frequency algorithms.\r\n\r\n\r\nCourse References:\r\nDiscrete-Time Signal Processing by Alan V. Oppenheim and Ronald W. Schafer, 3rd edition, 2010, Prentice Hall, Upper Saddle River, NJ.\r\n\r\nReference Books:(1) Digital Signal Processing by John G. Proakis and Dimitris K. Manolakis, 4th edition, 2007, Prentice Hall, Upper Saddle River, NJ. (2) Digital Signal Processing by Sanjit Mitra, 4th edition, 2011, McGraw-Hill, New York, NY.\r\n\r\nPre requisite:EE1101 Signals and Systems', '1', '3', '2022-02-21 04:21:34'),
(69, 0, 13, '1', '9', 2019, '4', 'EE2019', 'Analog Systems & Lab', '17', 'Course Details:\r\nCourse Objectives: Learning various fundamental concepts of analog systems such as open loop system, Active-RC Analog Filters, Op-amp based building blocks, feedback theory, stability of a closed loop system, compensation, voltage and current regulation, etc. Applying the above concepts in building an analog system prototype. Learning Outcomes: By the end of this course, students should be able to understand the fundamental concepts of analog systems and applying the same in real world applications.\r\n\r\nCourse Content:Basics of operational amplifier, op-amp based building blocks, linear and non-linear system, feedback theory, negative/positive feedback, stability criterion, bode plot with gain and phase margin, compensation, passive and active-RC analog filters, RLC filters, voltage and current regulators, pulse width modulation, AC coupling input and output and oscillators.\r\n\r\n\r\nCourse References:\r\nMicroelectronic Circuits: Theory and Applications (International Version) Paperback â€“ 11 Mar 2013 by A. Sedra, K. Smith, A. Chandorkar Publisher: Oxford; Sixth edition (11 March 2013) ISBN-13: 978-0198089131\r\n\r\nReference Books:Class notes and lab manual', '1', '3', '2022-02-21 04:21:34'),
