(270, 0, 53, '2', '51', 2020, '2', 'PH1040', 'Physics Lab ? II', '4', 'Course Details:\r\nCourse details :\r\nExperiments in Electricity, Magnetism, Optics and Atomic.\r\n\r\n\r\nCourse References:\r\nReferences:\r\n1. Smith E.V. - Manual of Experiments in Applied Physics, London, Butterworth, 1970. 2. Workshop B.L., and Flint H.P. -Advanced Practical Physics for Students, Methuen and Co. Ltd. London. 3. Jerrad H.G. and Mc Neil D.B. -Theoretical and Experimental Physics. 4. Fretter W.B. - Introduction to Experimental Physics, Blackiee, 5. M. Nelkon and J.M. Ogborn - Advanced Level Practical Physics,English Language Book Society, 1955.', '1', '3', '2022-02-22 12:43:23'),
(271, 0, 53, '2', '51', 2020, '2', 'CY1030', 'Chemistry Lab', '3', 'Course Details:\r\nCourse Contents :\r\nVolumetric analysis involving acid-base, redox, precipitation and complexometric titrations. Analysis of ores and alloys. Preparation of simple inorganic compounds. Determinations of molecular weight, distribution coefficient, equilibrium constant, rate constant. Experiments in phase rule. Preparation and properties of simple organic compounds, determination of phenol and formalin.\r\n\r\n\r\nCourse References:\r\nReferences:\r\n1. A.I. Vogel, A Text of Quantitative Inorganic Analysis, ELBS, London. 2. Shoemaker D.P. and Garland C.W., Experiments in Physical Chemistry, McGraw Hill, London. 3. Dey B.B. and Seetharaman M.V., Laboratory Manual of Organic Chemistry,', '1', '3', '2022-02-22 12:43:23');
